# No Abbreviations in Variable and Parameter Names

Use full, descriptive names for all variables, parameters, and destructured bindings. Do not use single-letter abbreviations like `c`, `s`, `h`, `b`, `d`, `p`, `k`, `n`, `r`, `w`, `t`, or `x` for domain concepts.

## Examples

Bad:
```ts
function resolve(c: number, s: number, h: number, b: number) { ... }
const [c, s, h, b] = key.split(',').map(Number);
const d = DICE[color];
result.reduce((s, d) => s + d.probability, 0);
```

Good:
```ts
function resolve(crits: number, surges: number, hits: number, blanks: number) { ... }
const [crits, surges, hits, blanks] = key.split(',').map(Number);
const die = DICE[color];
result.reduce((acc, entry) => acc + entry.probability, 0);
```

Standard loop counters (`i`, `j`) are acceptable. All other variables should have descriptive names that make the code readable without context.
